children.name: line a2
children.definition: line a long, thin, continuous mark on a surface:đường kẻ
examples: the teacher had put a red line through the first sentence.
mike drew a line along the wall to show where the tiles would come up to.
straight line
use your ruler to draw a straight line.
dotted linea line made up of dots that is marked on paper, especially to show the place wheresomeone must write their name:
sign on the dotted line, please.
the dotted line on the map shows the path that goes from the church down to the river.
fold the paper along the dotted line.
lined[adj] paper that is lined has lines printed across it : có đường kẻ
a letter written on pale blue lined paper

children.name: a line of writing or numbers
column c1
children.definition: column/ˈkɒləmǁˈkɑː-/  a line of numbers written under each other, that goes down a page: cột
examples: ▪ sales totals are shown in this column.
▪ add up the numbers in the column on the right.

children.name: line b1
children.definition: line/laɪn/  a line of writing that goes across a page: hàng , dòng
examples: ▪ martin opened the letter and read the first few lines - it was bad news.
▪ start reading at line 12.
line of
▪ a few lines of poetry

children.name: stripe b1
children.definition: stripe a straight line of colour on cloth, paper etc, usually part of a pattern where the line is repeated many times: sọc , viền, vằn
examples: the american flag has red and white stripes.
he was wearing a grey suit with narrow blue stripes.
my horse had a big white stripe down the middle of his nose.
striped/stripyuk [adj] spoken sth which is striped or stripy has a pattern on it which is made of many narrow coloured lines which are close together:
he was wearing a navy blue suit and a striped shirt.
stripey socks
red and black striped/pink and blue striped etc
my aunt knitted me a blue and white striped sweater for christmas.

children.name: band c2
children.definition: band a thick coloured line: vệt
examples: ▪ a black snake with orange bands around its back
band of
▪ there was a band of yellow in the rock.
▪ how many bands of colour are there in a rainbow?

children.name: streak x
children.definition: streak a coloured line, especially one that is not straight or that has been made without any plan or pattern: vệt, đường
examples: her hair was brown, with streaks of gold.
karen’s dress had a big streak of red wine down the front.
‘what have you been doing?’ asked his mother, pointing at the streaks of dried mud on his arms and legs.

children.name: a line on the ground or on the surface of sth
line a2
children.definition: line/laɪn/  đường kẻ
examples: ▪ if the ball goes over this line, it’s out of play.
yellow linea yellow line painted on the street which means that you cannot park there
▪ monica got a fine yesterday for parking on a yellow line.

children.name: rut x
children.definition: rut a deep line made in a dirt track by the wheels of vehicles: vết xe, vết bánh xe
examples: ▪ the road to the farm had deep ruts in it.
▪ the carriage became stuck in a rut, and we all had to get out and push.
rutted[adj] having many deep ruts
▪ gradually the road became more rutted and muddy.

children.name: tracks b2
children.definition: track a line on the ground that are left by the wheels of a vehicle: vết bánh xe
examples: ▪ the police were busy examining the tyre tracks of the two vehicles which were involved in the accident.
▪ we followed the tracks down a lane and arrived at an abandoned farmhouse.

children.name: groove x
children.definition: groove a thin line that has been cut into a surface, for example on a record: đường rãnh, đường xoi, đường rạch khía
examples: the record player needle kept jumping out of the grooves.
then you cut a groove into the wood, so that the two pieces can be slotted together.

children.name: furrow x
children.definition: furrow one of many long lines which have been dug in a field in order to plant crops: luống cày
examples: all around the furrows in the fields were filled with snow.

children.name: line c2
children.definition: line several things that are standing next to each other or one behind the other :
examples: in a line
maisie had arranged her teddy bears in a line on the bed.
line of
in front of the house there is a line of tall trees.

children.name: row b1
children.definition: row  a line of things that have been deliberately put next to each other, especially one of several lines that are arranged one behind the other:
examples: ▪ the tiny cottages had been built in long rows.
▪ they put a row of chairs out for the visitors.
▪ julie arranged her perfumes and creams in neat rows on the dressing table.
row upon rowmany rows
▪ the back wall was covered with row upon row of files.

children.name: bank x
children.definition: bank a line of computers, televisions, or other electrical equipment:
examples: bank of
fans who couldn’t get into the stadium watched the match on banks of tv monitors outside.
the scientists sit behind banks of computers, giving instructions to the crew of the spaceship.

children.name: tier x
children.definition: tier one of many rows of seats in a theatre, concert hall etc, which are at different levels:
examples: tier of
▪ we always sat in the top tier of seats.
▪ mason occupied two spaces on a tier of seats normally reserved for the board of directors and important visitors.

children.name: to draw or mark a line on sth
draw a line a2
children.definition: draw a line/ˌdrɔː ə ˈlaɪn/
examples: ▪ the teacher drew a line on the blackboard.
▪ someone’s drawn a line through my name and written in theirs.

children.name: underline b1
children.definition: underline/ˌʌndəʳˈlaɪn/  to draw a line under a word in order to make people notice it:
examples: ▪ don’t forget to underline the title of the essay.
▪ all the mistakes had been underlined in red ink.

children.name: rule x
children.definition: rule/ruːl/  formal to draw a straight line using a ruler or other straight edge:
examples: ▪ he ruled three lines under the title of his essay.
▪ she divided the page into four by ruling two diagonal lines across it.

children.name: queue b1
children.definition: queuebritish /lineamerican c2  a number of people who are standing one behind another, waiting to do sth: hàng người
examples: ▪ the queen is walking slowly along the lines of soldiers, occasionally stopping to ask a question.
▪ there was a queue of about fifteen people at the bus stop.
queue for
▪ the line for the movie went right around the block.
form a queue/linemake a queue/line
▪ the teacher got the children to form a line before they went into the hall.
▪ the women who were waiting outside the toilets began to form a queue.
in the queue/in a linepart of the queue
▪ excuse me, are you in the queue?
▪ the photographer asked us to stand in a line.

children.name: row b1
children.definition: row a line of people who have been arranged to stand or sit next to each other, especially when there are several lines of people arranged one behind another: hàng ngang
examples: ▪ can you see me in the photo? i’m in the back row on the left.
in a row
▪ the hotel staff stood in a row to greet their important guests.

children.name: in single file x
children.definition: in single file if a group of people walk in single file, they walk one behind another in a line: nối đuôi nhau, thành một hàng
examples: ▪ the path was so narrow that we had to walk in single file.

children.name: column x
children.definition: column/ˈkɒləmǁˈkɑː-/  a long moving line of people, especially soldiers:
examples: ▪ the column of french soldiers passed us on their way to the battlefront.
▪ columns of men and women were making their way towards the central square.

children.name: to stand in a line of people
stand in line c2
children.definition: stand/wait/be in linealsostand/wait on lineamerican  to stand in a line of people who are waiting to do sth:
examples: ▪ jerry joined the crowd of people who were waiting in line outside the stadium.
▪ standing in line for hours at some government office was not exactly my idea of fun.
to do something
▪ are you in line to get tickets?

children.name: queue b2
children.definition: queue british to stand in a line of people who are waiting to do sth: xếp hàng
examples: we had to queue for hours in the rain.
queue to do something
one of the other passengers who was queueing to get on the train suddenly had a heart attack.
queue for
thousands queued for tickets to see the final.

children.name: line c2
children.definition: line if many people line a street, they stand next to each other in lines along the sides of it, especially in order to see an important person or event:
examples: hundreds of people lined the streets to see the football team go by.
the route taken by the queen was lined with crowds of people waving flags.

children.name: to arrange things or people in a line
line up b2
children.definition: line up/ˌlaɪn ˈʌp/
examples: line up somebody/something
▪ he lined up the plates on the table in front of them.
line somebody/something up
▪ they lined the prisoners up and shot them.
▪ the horses were being lined up for the start of the race.

children.name: parade
children.definition: /pəˈreɪd/  an event in which a line of people such as musicians, dancers etc, or a line of decorated vehicles, go down the street while other people watch them in order to celebrate something:
examples: ▪ a lot of soldiers were missing from the victory parade.
▪ when johnson arrived home after the championships a big parade was held in his honour.
